":"1254","Abt. 1257":"about 1257","1210":"1210","about 1231":"about 1231","1208":"1208","1306":"1306","Pott Shrigley, Cheshire, England":"Pott Shrigley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Chorley, Cheshire, England":"Chorley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Downes, Derbyshire,England":"Downe, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Taxal, Cheshire, England":"Taxal, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Downes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Shropshire and Staffordshire): variant of   Down   with plural or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Irish (counties Clare and Limerick): shortened Anglicized form of Irish Gaelic <b>Ó Dubháin</b> (see   Doane  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Down","meanings":["English (Devon): topographic name for someone who lived on or near a down or low hill, from Middle English <i>dun(e)</i>, <i>doun(e)</i> (Old English <i>dūn</i>) ‘down, low hill’. See also   Downer  .","English (Devon): possibly in some cases a patronymic from the Old English personal name <i>Dūn</i>, but later names of this origin cannot reliably be distinguished from those originating from the topographic sense. See   Dunn   2."]},{"name":"Downs","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Downes  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":7,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":16,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":51,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Lord Robert Downes II was born in 1208, in Chorley, Cheshire, England, his father, Robert de Downes, was 32 and his mother, Mrs Robert de Downes, was 31. He had at least 1 son with Margery. He died in February 1273, in Pott Shrigley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 65."},"et":{"1208–February 1273":"1208–veebruar 1273","1208–1273":"1208–1273","1215–1254":"1215–1254","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1257–Male":"1257–Sur